01:01:00.800 --> 01:01:04.600
All of us are very political oriented, OK?

01:01:04.600 --> 01:01:05.920
Very much so.

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:08.280
So we came up in a political environment.

01:01:08.280 --> 01:01:15.480
So when in the mid 1940s, my dad had heard about the NAACP

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:17.840
started up, OK?

01:01:17.840 --> 01:01:24.360
And he and eight other black men

01:01:24.360 --> 01:01:28.360
established the farest-counter branch of the NAACP.

01:01:28.360 --> 01:01:30.160
It was nine of them that started it.

01:01:30.160 --> 01:01:31.800
And they held secret meetings.

01:01:31.800 --> 01:01:34.320
And they went to the meetings at night.

01:01:34.320 --> 01:01:39.120
The nine black men in the Hattensperf area

01:01:39.120 --> 01:01:44.000
that founded the farest-counter branch of the NAACP.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:50.600
And it was around 1945, the mid 1940s, OK?

01:01:50.600 --> 01:01:54.440
And at that time, they had the meetings at night.

01:01:54.440 --> 01:01:58.080
And my dad would always let us know, let me know.

01:01:58.080 --> 01:02:00.400
I'm going to NAACP meeting because it

01:02:00.400 --> 01:02:04.600
was an underground type organization on that time.

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:10.480
And he continued to go to these meetings very religiously.

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:15.400
And then when he go to the meeting, he would come home

01:02:15.400 --> 01:02:16.600
and we'd be working there.

01:02:16.600 --> 01:02:19.680
And he'd tell us, tell me and my whole brother

01:02:19.680 --> 01:02:23.960
what was going on as we did our work, all right?

01:02:23.960 --> 01:02:34.040
And as a result of him being a part of that organization,

01:02:34.040 --> 01:02:37.760
and he let us know by just a conversation

01:02:37.760 --> 01:02:42.440
that there was, it had something to do with politics.

01:02:42.440 --> 01:02:42.760
OK?

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:46.120
It had something to do with voting, OK?

01:02:46.120 --> 01:02:57.800
So in about 1946, yeah, I think I was around 16, 17 years old, maybe.

01:02:57.800 --> 01:03:03.120
My dad started taking me with him even before then when he did business.

01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:06.840
I'd go with him when he paid the property tax.

01:03:06.840 --> 01:03:10.520
And at the same time, you paid the property tax to the sheriff.

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:14.160
Sheriff was a tax collector in Faris County.

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:17.720
He would also pay his poll tax.

01:03:17.720 --> 01:03:19.520
And when he leave the sheriff's office,

01:03:19.520 --> 01:03:23.480
he'd go down the hall to the voter registration office

01:03:23.480 --> 01:03:26.040
and pay his poll tax.

01:03:26.040 --> 01:03:31.960
Well, on this one occasion, he went to pay the poll tax.

01:03:31.960 --> 01:03:35.360
And may have been the first, I don't know what happened, proud to then.

01:03:35.360 --> 01:03:36.160
He went then.

01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:37.560
He pulled out his receipt.

01:03:37.560 --> 01:03:39.120
He had his hand.

01:03:39.120 --> 01:03:43.040
And there was this white man behind the counter.

01:03:43.040 --> 01:03:47.760
And he walked up me asking, I knew who my dad was, I don't know, being a country town.

01:03:47.760 --> 01:03:48.880
Yeah, what do you want?

01:03:48.880 --> 01:03:50.280
That's how I paid my poll tax.

01:03:50.280 --> 01:03:52.800
I want to register.

01:03:52.800 --> 01:03:54.800
And he looked at him.

01:03:54.800 --> 01:03:57.720
It's just kind of like staring at him, you know, why are you here?

01:03:57.720 --> 01:04:01.400
I remember that because I'm old enough not to know how you treat my dad.

01:04:01.400 --> 01:04:09.000
And he gave my dad a card, like a full-baked card, a six-bate, and he had some writing on it.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:10.360
He said, read that and tell me what to say.

01:04:10.360 --> 01:04:12.920
And then he went on back and said, I'm.

01:04:12.920 --> 01:04:16.320
My dad read the information on the card.

01:04:16.320 --> 01:04:20.400
And finally, he says, sir, I'm finished.

01:04:20.400 --> 01:04:23.280
And the guy came up and looked at him and looked at him.

01:04:23.280 --> 01:04:24.520
He said, all right, tell me what you read.

01:04:24.520 --> 01:04:26.040
My dad told him.

01:04:26.040 --> 01:04:27.840
He says that's not what he said.

01:04:27.840 --> 01:04:29.520
And that was end of it.

01:04:29.520 --> 01:04:35.320
Now, here's a man, my father, who had helped me with my lesson.

01:04:35.320 --> 01:04:36.880
He was in business.

01:04:36.880 --> 01:04:38.360
He was running a business.

01:04:38.360 --> 01:04:40.160
And he couldn't interpret what was on the card.

01:04:40.160 --> 01:04:42.480
Now, I was old enough to know that's not true.

01:04:42.480 --> 01:04:44.160
That aggravated me so.

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:48.800
Because what you did, you just denied a man that I cared a lot about.

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:53.000
Hey, you just told him, you don't know what you're talking about.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:54.560
That didn't hit me very well.

01:04:54.560 --> 01:05:00.760
Now, I didn't get mad about it, but I saw that as strange because I'd never seen this up front that close.

01:05:00.760 --> 01:05:03.560
I'm sure it's happened other places.

01:05:03.560 --> 01:05:11.480
And from that time on, he may have continued.

01:05:11.480 --> 01:05:17.680
I didn't go with him anymore, but I don't know what he did or did not.

01:05:17.680 --> 01:05:24.440
And the next time I heard anything about him becoming involved was when he became president

01:05:24.440 --> 01:05:31.120
of the local NAACB during the mid-50s.

01:05:31.120 --> 01:05:38.160
And as a result of the Supreme Court ruling on the school segregation problem, I was at

01:05:38.160 --> 01:05:40.160
Brown versus Board Education in Kansas.

01:05:40.160 --> 01:05:41.160
Something like that.

01:05:41.160 --> 01:05:43.000
I think that's right.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:45.160
Mississippi then tightened up.

01:05:45.160 --> 01:05:47.160
It really tightened up.

01:05:47.160 --> 01:05:49.160
Hey, we're not going to have no school integration here.

01:05:49.160 --> 01:05:52.800
My days already involved in the NAACB by then.

01:05:52.800 --> 01:05:54.720
And he's out of the closet.

01:05:54.720 --> 01:05:56.480
The organization is out of the closet.

01:05:56.480 --> 01:05:57.960
It's well known.

01:05:57.960 --> 01:06:08.000
And then that's when he became targeted by the hostile forces out there.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:11.880
What is that first incident that you saw or the one that you witnessed?

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:14.640
Did he say anything to you when you were riding home that day?

01:06:14.640 --> 01:06:15.640
Did he say anything to you?

01:06:15.640 --> 01:06:16.640
Did he talk to you about what happened?

01:06:16.640 --> 01:06:17.640
No, he did not.

01:06:17.640 --> 01:06:18.640
No.

01:06:18.640 --> 01:06:23.080
I think, going that time, I can only think that that was such a routine practice of being

01:06:23.080 --> 01:06:24.080
denied.

01:06:24.080 --> 01:06:29.480
Maybe he would not be there to him, so maybe he'd go with other blacks.

01:06:29.480 --> 01:06:31.320
He just suck it up and move on.

01:06:31.320 --> 01:06:33.320
Yeah.

01:06:33.320 --> 01:06:38.320
And you said when he was president in the mid-1950s, people knew who he was.

01:06:38.320 --> 01:06:40.840
Oh, yeah, without a doubt.

01:06:40.840 --> 01:06:43.440
And you said that's when the harassment started.

01:06:43.440 --> 01:06:44.440
Yeah.

01:06:44.440 --> 01:06:46.440
That's when the harassment started then, okay?

01:06:46.440 --> 01:06:47.440
Do what?

01:06:47.440 --> 01:06:48.440
You probably weren't hard on him.

01:06:48.440 --> 01:06:51.000
I wasn't here, but he told you about it.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:52.000
Yeah, he talked about it.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:55.040
Can you tell us what he said to you or what you know about it?

01:06:55.040 --> 01:06:56.040
Yeah.

01:06:56.040 --> 01:07:06.400
That's the first time, you know, the racial climate was changing.

01:07:06.400 --> 01:07:09.360
You know, the tension was rising.

01:07:09.360 --> 01:07:16.960
And this friendly atmosphere that we once had there was disappearing.

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:20.920
Now he is how I experienced it.

01:07:20.920 --> 01:07:23.480
I went in Air Force 1951.

01:07:23.520 --> 01:07:29.440
I came home around 1955 at that time after I had re-enlisted and chose Air Force as a

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:30.440
career.

01:07:30.440 --> 01:07:33.840
And I was a staff sergeant, did well during my first investment.

01:07:33.840 --> 01:07:38.800
And I stopped at the local white grocery store that had been in the community before

01:07:38.800 --> 01:07:44.040
my dead bill, too, because we had a relationship with that family, because that's where we did

01:07:44.040 --> 01:07:45.560
our trading.

01:07:45.560 --> 01:07:47.040
And I stopped there to get some gas.

01:07:47.040 --> 01:07:53.360
Now I went in with a real friendly atmosphere and the wife of the store owner, she

01:07:53.360 --> 01:08:00.160
was there and I spoke to her and they had one son and he was several years younger than

01:08:00.160 --> 01:08:03.720
me, but I saw him grow up.

01:08:03.720 --> 01:08:06.400
So I asked her, I said, well, where is your son?

01:08:06.400 --> 01:08:09.560
I called him by his name and she said, you mean Mr.

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:11.120
Someone's Son?

01:08:11.120 --> 01:08:16.400
Well, here I am now 25 years old, 26.

01:08:16.400 --> 01:08:22.920
And she want me to call us on who's probably still a teenager, Mr. Never saw that before.

01:08:23.880 --> 01:08:30.120
And I stopped at another grocery store in the community on down, coming toward Hattiesburg

01:08:30.120 --> 01:08:32.280
where we would stop occasionally.

01:08:32.280 --> 01:08:36.960
And I went in there just to buy something because I feel comfortable being at home and

01:08:36.960 --> 01:08:41.160
the grocery store owner there, he said, oh, you're in there?

01:08:41.160 --> 01:08:43.640
You're up now, and I said, yes I am.

01:08:43.640 --> 01:08:50.280
I was stationed in Nebraska, Omaha, and off of Air Force Base.

01:08:50.280 --> 01:08:53.680
And he says, what's it like being up there?

01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:54.680
Okay?

01:08:54.680 --> 01:08:56.480
Are they different?

01:08:56.480 --> 01:08:57.480
Okay.

01:08:57.480 --> 01:09:03.280
So he was quizzing me on my being outside of that in Mississippi environment.

01:09:03.280 --> 01:09:04.280
Have you been growing?

01:09:04.280 --> 01:09:09.080
And how had it affected me being in a more integrated area?

01:09:09.080 --> 01:09:10.960
And I picked up on that immediately.

01:09:10.960 --> 01:09:13.840
He was wanting to know if you've been ruined or not.

01:09:13.840 --> 01:09:16.920
I'd been ruined, that's exactly right.

01:09:16.920 --> 01:09:23.720
So that's how I knew then that the things had changed and my dad was getting into a situation.

01:09:23.720 --> 01:09:29.320
But I didn't really focus on it because it had not been any open violence.

01:09:29.320 --> 01:09:36.600
It was just a rise in the recognition that things about to happen in Mississippi now that

01:09:36.600 --> 01:09:39.480
the mass does not want to happen.

01:09:39.480 --> 01:09:44.680
And you're not going to be treated quite as kindly and as friendly as it was because

01:09:44.680 --> 01:09:48.280
now you're starting to threaten our way of life.

01:09:48.280 --> 01:09:49.520
And I had to look back on it.

01:09:49.520 --> 01:09:51.760
I didn't recognize it at that time.

01:09:51.760 --> 01:09:56.760
So what I did then was I didn't go into these places.

01:09:56.760 --> 01:09:58.600
I just kind of stayed away from them.

01:09:58.600 --> 01:09:59.600
Yeah.

01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:02.960
Did your father talk to you about the changing atmosphere?

01:10:02.960 --> 01:10:06.080
Did you just know it from your own experience?

01:10:06.080 --> 01:10:09.320
When I would visit home, he didn't have to say it.

01:10:09.320 --> 01:10:10.320
He was obvious.

01:10:10.320 --> 01:10:11.320
Yeah.

01:10:11.320 --> 01:10:13.840
And I was obvious.

01:10:13.840 --> 01:10:18.840
He would, for example, I came home with my family at that time because I had a couple of kids

01:10:18.840 --> 01:10:20.960
and we stayed there with him.

01:10:20.960 --> 01:10:27.200
And he says, hey, be careful where you go and you hear.

01:10:27.200 --> 01:10:32.000
At night time, we don't walk and get in front of windows.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:34.920
And also we've seen some harassment here.

01:10:34.920 --> 01:10:38.560
There was a gun in that room where you're going to be.

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:41.080
If you hear anything, hey, be aware of it.

01:10:41.640 --> 01:10:44.280
Well, being military, that was a big deal.

01:10:44.280 --> 01:10:45.880
Come out of the family, we had guns.

01:10:45.880 --> 01:10:46.640
Hey, that's okay.

01:10:46.640 --> 01:10:48.480
I'm comfortable with that environment.

01:10:48.480 --> 01:10:51.080
So I saw the difference happening then.

01:10:51.080 --> 01:10:54.000
It's a real change to have to take all those precautions.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:55.560
They have to take all those precautions.

01:10:55.560 --> 01:10:56.840
That is exactly right.

01:10:57.880 --> 01:10:58.560
Sure.

01:10:58.560 --> 01:11:01.520
Can you tell me about your own military experience?

01:11:01.520 --> 01:11:03.640
What happened when you got drafted?

01:11:03.640 --> 01:11:11.000
What I happened when I got drafted was it was doing the height of the Korean War.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:13.720
And there was troops everywhere.

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:16.160
And when I'm in my everywhere, you know,

01:11:16.160 --> 01:11:18.480
when you get into that military environment.

01:11:18.480 --> 01:11:26.480
And I left home on a bus and went to Jackson along with some other recruits.

01:11:26.480 --> 01:11:31.200
Went to the recruiting stand, at the reporting place.

01:11:31.200 --> 01:11:38.800
And it was on a tri-state bus, a great one, on the other.

01:11:38.800 --> 01:11:42.520
And there were whites and black guys on there.

01:11:42.520 --> 01:11:44.480
And maybe some other passengers don't remember exactly.

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:48.280
But we got there and checked in.

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:49.520
The day was far along.

01:11:49.520 --> 01:11:52.000
They gave us some food and took us to Motel.

01:11:53.480 --> 01:11:54.960
Well, there was no Motel for whites.

01:11:54.960 --> 01:11:56.240
We went out on Ferris Street.

01:11:56.240 --> 01:11:59.000
That was a black hotel down there, okay?

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:01.160
Well, I'd been on Ferris Street, so, yeah, I'm all right.

01:12:01.160 --> 01:12:02.160
We're free.

01:12:02.160 --> 01:12:04.760
And the white ones, they went.

01:12:04.760 --> 01:12:07.640
And the next morning got up and they picked us up in the bus and

01:12:07.680 --> 01:12:09.760
scared us to the induction center.

01:12:09.760 --> 01:12:12.600
And that's when the processing took place, you know,

01:12:12.600 --> 01:12:16.720
along stripping down, doing your physicals and all.

01:12:16.720 --> 01:12:18.320
And getting rid of the ship us off.

01:12:18.320 --> 01:12:20.000
From there, the next day, we left, no,

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:22.480
we ended up with the San Antonio, Texas.

01:12:22.480 --> 01:12:26.600
The lack of an Air Force base, which is a major Air Force training base.

01:12:26.600 --> 01:12:29.880
And now I mean, there were troops all over the place.

01:12:29.880 --> 01:12:34.880
And we were sleeping in tents because the permanent structures were all full.

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:38.160
And I'm gonna stay there just about three weeks.

01:12:38.160 --> 01:12:41.280
And they keep us busy, guys busy.

01:12:43.920 --> 01:12:48.080
Most of what got up, dressed, do your military thing.

01:12:48.080 --> 01:12:50.920
And they've got and picked up big rocks, put them on pile.

01:12:51.920 --> 01:12:54.760
And then the next day we'd come along and we'd pick up the smaller ones,

01:12:54.760 --> 01:12:56.600
put them in piles, okay?

01:12:56.600 --> 01:12:57.720
Let's keep it busy.

01:12:57.720 --> 01:12:59.600
You thought I'm kidding, that's a fact.

01:12:59.600 --> 01:13:03.040
All right, and then during the night, they spread them all out again and whatever.

01:13:03.040 --> 01:13:03.880
All right.

01:13:04.600 --> 01:13:07.360
But anyway, you went through all that stuff, you know,

01:13:07.360 --> 01:13:10.320
my mom and my 22 years old, been working on the fall.

01:13:10.320 --> 01:13:12.320
Yeah, I'm not yet picking up rocks.

01:13:13.320 --> 01:13:15.480
And then we went on a ship,

01:13:15.480 --> 01:13:19.200
this out there, a ship with Air Force base in Wichita Falls, Texas.

01:13:19.200 --> 01:13:21.120
That's why I did my basic training.

01:13:21.120 --> 01:13:26.640
From basic training, I was assigned to French and Seymour and Air Base

01:13:26.640 --> 01:13:30.360
in Cheyenne, Wyoming, for my tech training.

01:13:30.440 --> 01:13:36.040
And that was a tele-type training school there,

01:13:36.040 --> 01:13:39.080
along with other training facilities too,

01:13:39.080 --> 01:13:41.200
for in the communications field.

01:13:41.200 --> 01:13:43.520
And there was a motor transportation and bigot,

01:13:43.520 --> 01:13:45.840
then kids had to drive trucks and stuff.

01:13:45.840 --> 01:13:48.960
Let me ask you, so how did you feel about being drafted?

01:13:51.080 --> 01:13:52.720
I tried to try my best day out of it.

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:54.880
My dad tried to get me deferred.

01:13:54.880 --> 01:13:56.840
And I didn't want to go.

01:13:56.840 --> 01:13:58.560
No, I did not want to go.

01:13:58.600 --> 01:14:02.360
All because I'm comfortable where I am.

01:14:02.360 --> 01:14:03.480
Yeah.

01:14:03.480 --> 01:14:07.760
What about were you drafted specifically into the Air Force?

01:14:07.760 --> 01:14:08.840
Or did you have any say?

01:14:08.840 --> 01:14:10.160
Oh, that's the piece I missed.

01:14:10.160 --> 01:14:11.560
No, let me tell you how that happened.

01:14:11.560 --> 01:14:13.080
All right.

01:14:13.080 --> 01:14:18.200
One, there may be a little month, a little over,

01:14:20.200 --> 01:14:23.880
proud to going in the Air Force.

01:14:23.960 --> 01:14:28.560
I received a letter from the,

01:14:31.880 --> 01:14:33.640
that'll name, Local Boy.

01:14:33.640 --> 01:14:34.440
The draft boy?

01:14:34.440 --> 01:14:36.200
Brack Boy.

01:14:36.200 --> 01:14:39.600
Directing the I report for induction

01:14:39.600 --> 01:14:43.200
on the 15th of September, 1951.

01:14:44.320 --> 01:14:45.920
And I looked at it and I said,

01:14:45.920 --> 01:14:48.560
okay, well, I'm getting ready to get out of here.

01:14:48.560 --> 01:14:50.800
So I'm living in the house of my dad,

01:14:50.800 --> 01:14:53.320
and I told him, hey, this is what this is about.

01:14:53.320 --> 01:14:58.160
So I start preparing to go off to the Army.

01:14:58.160 --> 01:15:00.120
Because that's where the guys were going, right?

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:06.120
My uncle, my dad's baby sister's husband

01:15:06.120 --> 01:15:11.120
was in the 92nd Infantry in Italy,

01:15:13.320 --> 01:15:16.760
a ground foot soldier, fault.

01:15:16.760 --> 01:15:20.080
And I told him, he said, no, no, you don't want to do that.

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:20.840
Uh-oh.

01:15:20.840 --> 01:15:22.920
Then I had a couple of other black guys in the community

01:15:22.920 --> 01:15:25.840
that was in combat, he said, you don't want to do that.

01:15:25.840 --> 01:15:28.920
He said, hey, go to the Navy or the Air Force.

01:15:28.920 --> 01:15:31.200
Don't get caught up in this Army thing.

01:15:31.200 --> 01:15:33.800
And after they told me that, I said, okay.

01:15:33.800 --> 01:15:38.800
So I procrastinated up until the 10th of September.

01:15:38.800 --> 01:15:40.960
You didn't give yourself much?

01:15:40.960 --> 01:15:41.960
No.

01:15:41.960 --> 01:15:44.760
And I said, look, I got to make up a man.

01:15:44.760 --> 01:15:46.640
So I went to the Air Force Recruiter.

01:15:46.640 --> 01:15:49.400
He enhanced bird is in the basement of the old post office,

01:15:49.400 --> 01:15:50.680
downtown, yeah.

01:15:50.680 --> 01:15:53.920
And I walked in and there was an Air Force Recruiter,

01:15:53.920 --> 01:15:56.520
armor recruiter, Navy Recruiter.

01:15:56.520 --> 01:15:58.320
I'm not sure whether they had a Marine or not.

01:15:58.320 --> 01:16:01.080
And I saw the Air Force not winning that door.

01:16:01.080 --> 01:16:03.200
And that sergeancy said, can I help you?

01:16:03.200 --> 01:16:06.320
Now, I told him, I said, I like to volunteer for the Air Force.

01:16:06.320 --> 01:16:08.760
So he gave me some papers that fell out and, you know,

01:16:08.760 --> 01:16:11.160
and I took some tests of whatever.

01:16:11.160 --> 01:16:13.640
And he said, well, when you want to leave,

01:16:13.640 --> 01:16:14.960
I said, can I leave today?

01:16:14.960 --> 01:16:19.400
He said, no, the bus is already gone.

01:16:19.400 --> 01:16:20.560
He said, we're about in the morning,

01:16:20.560 --> 01:16:21.600
be down here at seven o'clock.

01:16:21.600 --> 01:16:23.520
I said, OK, I'll be here.

01:16:23.520 --> 01:16:26.000
So at seven o'clock, I reported to the post office,

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:28.280
and they were there and they carried us down to the bus station,

01:16:28.280 --> 01:16:31.280
which is they all walked north street, you know,

01:16:31.280 --> 01:16:33.800
called a bus out the Jackson.

01:16:33.800 --> 01:16:43.240
And so after I got situated at Shepherd Air Force Base

01:16:43.240 --> 01:16:47.280
in basic training, which is in Wichita Falls, Texas.

01:16:47.280 --> 01:16:51.840
And that was it, by the way, in the early part of September

01:16:51.840 --> 01:17:01.960
of 1951, I was in my unit and my squad drilling with them

01:17:01.960 --> 01:17:06.400
out on the parade field going through my training.

01:17:06.400 --> 01:17:12.360
And in that group, we must have been about 30 guys

01:17:12.360 --> 01:17:15.520
in these squads.

01:17:15.520 --> 01:17:19.800
My name came out over the PA system,

01:17:19.800 --> 01:17:24.600
private Vernon, Dameron, Jr. report to the order room.

01:17:24.600 --> 01:17:26.520
I'm 22 years old.

01:17:26.520 --> 01:17:30.880
I'm in there with a bunch of guys, not 18, 19, maybe 20.

01:17:30.880 --> 01:17:32.960
I'm kind of like the old dude, OK?

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:35.280
Never a few left over in World War II.

01:17:35.280 --> 01:17:37.840
You know, that was coming back again.

01:17:37.840 --> 01:17:39.520
And but not very many.

01:17:39.520 --> 01:17:42.520
I don't know if it was one of them out, but anyway, I was

01:17:42.520 --> 01:17:44.280
saying, what have I done now?

01:17:44.280 --> 01:17:47.120
Because I'm in this middle-aged environment now.

01:17:47.120 --> 01:17:48.240
Your name come out.

01:17:48.240 --> 01:17:50.840
You don't remember anything that you did.

01:17:50.840 --> 01:17:52.440
What have I done?

01:17:52.440 --> 01:17:53.440
Right.

01:17:53.440 --> 01:17:56.160
And so squadly to call to a hall.

01:17:56.160 --> 01:18:00.040
This miss me from the group told me report to the order room.

01:18:00.040 --> 01:18:03.640
I went to the order room, reported to the first sergeant.

01:18:03.640 --> 01:18:04.400
He's two gentlemen.

01:18:04.400 --> 01:18:05.760
I won't talk with you.

01:18:05.760 --> 01:18:08.200
They went to me in clothes.

01:18:08.200 --> 01:18:10.280
And they asked me, your name?

01:18:10.280 --> 01:18:12.160
I told them burn up, they were junior.

01:18:12.160 --> 01:18:13.800
Let me see your dog tags.

01:18:13.800 --> 01:18:15.720
Dog tags, romma, they put them in dog tags out.

01:18:15.720 --> 01:18:17.160
And they checked them.

01:18:17.160 --> 01:18:18.960
That's who you are.

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:24.120
He said, you know your draft Dodger.

01:18:24.120 --> 01:18:25.280
No sir.

01:18:25.280 --> 01:18:26.480
I didn't know that.

01:18:26.480 --> 01:18:30.120
Well, didn't you get your notice from the local board?

01:18:30.120 --> 01:18:31.080
Lion's room and team.

01:18:31.080 --> 01:18:33.560
No sir.

01:18:33.560 --> 01:18:35.760
I didn't sign for it.

01:18:35.760 --> 01:18:38.560
Lion stood in flat foot.

01:18:38.560 --> 01:18:41.720
And he said, well, they sent you one.

01:18:41.720 --> 01:18:43.760
I said, no sir, I never got it.

01:18:43.760 --> 01:18:46.120
He said, well, OK.

01:18:46.120 --> 01:18:47.200
You already in now.

01:18:47.200 --> 01:18:48.120
I guess that's all right.

01:18:48.120 --> 01:18:49.560
Well, I guess it is all right.

01:18:49.560 --> 01:18:51.440
You're going to take me out and put me in the army?

01:18:51.440 --> 01:18:52.680
I wasn't thinking that for him.

01:18:52.680 --> 01:18:54.040
I'm thinking that now.

01:18:54.040 --> 01:18:58.000
And when we did that, well, the press variation dried up.

01:18:58.000 --> 01:18:59.920
And I got a hold of my nerves.

01:18:59.920 --> 01:19:02.440
And the first sergeant said, all right, get back to your unit.

01:19:02.440 --> 01:19:03.640
I went back to my unit.

01:19:03.640 --> 01:19:06.040
Did you know that that might happen?

01:19:06.040 --> 01:19:08.720
Or did you just know that was going to happen?

01:19:08.720 --> 01:19:09.720
No.

01:19:09.720 --> 01:19:11.960
And then he just flashed the badges on me.

01:19:11.960 --> 01:19:14.400
So they were from some kind of investigative unit.

01:19:14.400 --> 01:19:17.360
I don't know whether with the FBI or the local arm

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:20.800
investigators, you know, their own investigators.

01:19:20.800 --> 01:19:21.760
But no, they were federal.

01:19:21.760 --> 01:19:22.520
I know that though.

01:19:22.520 --> 01:19:24.480
They had a federal.

01:19:24.480 --> 01:19:26.280
That's a little nerve-wracking.

01:19:26.280 --> 01:19:27.040
Would all of them.

01:19:27.040 --> 01:19:29.800
And you came up with that?

01:19:29.800 --> 01:19:30.880
On your feet.

01:19:30.880 --> 01:19:31.880
Oh my.

01:19:31.880 --> 01:19:32.880
You don't be in 22 years old.

01:19:32.880 --> 01:19:34.080
You learn how to lie.

01:19:34.080 --> 01:19:35.600
You learn how to lie quick.

01:19:35.600 --> 01:19:36.600
Especially when you get in the band.

01:19:36.600 --> 01:19:38.080
It sounds like it came in handy.

01:19:38.080 --> 01:19:38.600
Yes, it is.

01:19:38.600 --> 01:19:39.360
That's a good skill.

01:19:39.360 --> 01:19:40.360
I guess.

01:19:40.360 --> 01:19:41.360
Yeah, very good.

01:19:41.360 --> 01:19:42.360
It worked.

01:19:42.360 --> 01:19:46.760
When you went into the military, how did you end up?

01:19:46.760 --> 01:19:49.600
You said you went to the communication school for teletype training.

01:19:49.600 --> 01:19:51.880
How did that come about?

01:19:51.880 --> 01:19:55.640
That's another phase that's very interesting.

01:19:55.640 --> 01:20:02.560
I was assigned to Fransity One Air Base in Chiang Wai-Homie and to become a teletype operator.

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:09.160
Being raised on a farm, or we had an old cash register.

01:20:09.160 --> 01:20:13.280
My dad found somewhere and it was manual.

01:20:13.280 --> 01:20:18.740
And now you're taking this farm, boy, who's going to use the drive in trucks, hauling logs,

01:20:18.740 --> 01:20:20.960
running tractor and all this.

01:20:20.960 --> 01:20:27.500
Yes, I had mechanical abilities, operation type, operating type abilities, but not for no

01:20:27.500 --> 01:20:29.000
typewriter, no teletype.

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:30.000
Yeah.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:31.800
No typewriter.

01:20:31.800 --> 01:20:37.760
And they assigned me that school and I started off and after that for a while, I was in this

01:20:37.760 --> 01:20:43.000
typing class, J-U-G-S-F-G-F-S-F.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:47.920
And I'm telling myself I don't want to be in a teletype operator.

01:20:47.920 --> 01:20:50.960
This doesn't fit me in my prior experience.

01:20:50.960 --> 01:20:55.880
And across this great big open field while I'm in big and everything is open, was a bunch

01:20:55.880 --> 01:21:00.600
of guys in training learning how to drive a truck with a trailer.

01:21:00.600 --> 01:21:01.600
I knew how to do that.

01:21:01.600 --> 01:21:05.840
I got back a truckload of Lumber Donald alley.

01:21:05.840 --> 01:21:11.840
And I'm sitting there in front of a typewriter and I can go to that just school and I can

01:21:11.840 --> 01:21:14.880
go right through that and build truck driver.

01:21:14.880 --> 01:21:17.360
And I want to have to deal with this typewriter.

01:21:17.360 --> 01:21:24.360
Well being the old-against community in my squadron, I had a relationship somehow with the

01:21:24.360 --> 01:21:26.120
first sergeant.

01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:28.840
You know, been around a little bit.

01:21:28.840 --> 01:21:30.920
And I started to be his runner.

01:21:30.920 --> 01:21:35.400
He asked me, he said, Damour, I need guys that carry messages from one outfit to another

01:21:35.400 --> 01:21:36.400
to the headquarters.

01:21:36.400 --> 01:21:37.400
You want to do that?

01:21:37.400 --> 01:21:40.160
That's doing my off time when I got off in the evening, okay?

01:21:40.160 --> 01:21:44.240
Well I'm doing this remedial training, me and two other guys trying to catch up in the

01:21:44.240 --> 01:21:45.400
typing.

01:21:45.400 --> 01:21:48.600
And then I would do that, you know, my off time, thinking I made a little something out

01:21:48.600 --> 01:21:49.880
of that.

01:21:49.880 --> 01:21:55.560
So doing that, time I was working with the first sergeant, things got real comfortable

01:21:55.560 --> 01:21:58.320
with my sergeant.

01:21:58.320 --> 01:22:00.840
I said, can I go in and talk to the captain?

01:22:00.840 --> 01:22:07.800
I want to go to the old here, is that that automotive training place to the truck driving

01:22:07.800 --> 01:22:09.800
school.

01:22:09.800 --> 01:22:12.880
And he said, man, they don't need you doing that, you're intelligent.

01:22:12.880 --> 01:22:18.200
Finally, which is one day, he said, okay, he made a appointment with me to see the captain.

01:22:18.200 --> 01:22:22.320
And I got all dressed up and went in and reported to the captain and gave him my experience

01:22:22.320 --> 01:22:24.800
in old driving truck, raised on the farm.

01:22:24.800 --> 01:22:27.960
And he said, and I know with this nice little smile on his face.

01:22:27.960 --> 01:22:30.760
And I thought I was getting over on him.

01:22:30.760 --> 01:22:35.080
And when I finished, he says, you know what, you got a lot of good experience.

01:22:35.080 --> 01:22:38.440
And they can use you over there.

01:22:38.440 --> 01:22:40.800
He said, but private, they might.

01:22:40.800 --> 01:22:46.080
He says, the Air Force needs come first.

01:22:46.080 --> 01:22:52.640
And I want you to go back down to that teletype school and be the best teletype operator in

01:22:52.640 --> 01:22:54.320
the outfit.

01:22:54.320 --> 01:22:57.520
And I'm going to burst into my bubble right in front of his desk.

01:22:57.520 --> 01:23:01.760
And when I went by the first sergeant, he said, I told you so.

01:23:01.760 --> 01:23:06.240
I went on back to the barracks and I got with it.

01:23:06.240 --> 01:23:07.240
It resigned yourself?

01:23:07.240 --> 01:23:08.240
Yes, I did.

01:23:08.240 --> 01:23:16.440
I learned how to type, graduated, and believe it or not, that was the best decision that

01:23:16.440 --> 01:23:20.920
was made for me by somebody else.

01:23:20.920 --> 01:23:26.960
That being a teletype operator moved me into the communications vein all the way to

01:23:26.960 --> 01:23:31.200
computers when I retired as a senior master sergeant.

01:23:31.200 --> 01:23:36.680
That ain't no way I would have been a senior master sergeant driving a truck.

01:23:36.680 --> 01:23:41.680
And I got promoted on my first enlistment because I was used to what, studying, I was

01:23:41.680 --> 01:23:43.160
used to commitment.

01:23:43.160 --> 01:23:46.680
So I didn't have no problem becoming a good title type operator.

01:23:46.680 --> 01:23:48.840
And it worked out real well.

01:23:48.840 --> 01:23:53.120
And I married two, one month before I went into Air Force.

01:23:53.120 --> 01:23:58.480
And by the time I finished my first enlistment at Tendell Air Force Base in Florida, where

01:23:58.480 --> 01:24:00.720
I was stationed, I was already a staff sergeant.

01:24:00.720 --> 01:24:03.800
I could take my family with me any place I went.

01:24:03.800 --> 01:24:07.680
And then assignment came up going to Europe.

01:24:07.680 --> 01:24:11.400
But proud to my first assignment, let me back up a moment.

01:24:11.400 --> 01:24:17.240
When I got out of Tendell Type School, my first assignment then was to a radar station

01:24:17.240 --> 01:24:20.160
in Omaha, Nebraska.

01:24:20.160 --> 01:24:21.840
Not today I was at a radar station.

01:24:21.840 --> 01:24:26.840
From there to Omaha, Alaska, a radar site, overlooking the Siberian streets, watching

01:24:26.840 --> 01:24:30.600
the Russians take off and land every day.

01:24:30.600 --> 01:24:34.000
They fly out and they leave you there for a year.

01:24:34.000 --> 01:24:35.000
Wow, isolated.

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:37.640
I married one month before I leave.

01:24:37.640 --> 01:24:40.520
My wife is pregnant with a baby.

01:24:40.520 --> 01:24:46.840
I'm wanting to be home and I'm sitting here now in this isolated place waiting for a year

01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:47.840
to pass.

01:24:47.840 --> 01:24:49.600
I must have been a...

01:24:49.600 --> 01:24:53.560
To me it was domesticated, purified, or whatever.

01:24:53.560 --> 01:24:54.560
But it was all work.

01:24:54.560 --> 01:24:55.560
Now, that's new.

01:24:55.560 --> 01:25:00.400
You work in SLL.

01:25:00.400 --> 01:25:04.680
And I cleaned up extra work in the office of the quarter to make extra money sent to my

01:25:04.680 --> 01:25:06.000
wife and all.

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:10.960
So when I came, when I was a sign from there, I had preference on the base because of

01:25:10.960 --> 01:25:11.960
this...

01:25:11.960 --> 01:25:12.960
Because of where you lived in?

01:25:12.960 --> 01:25:13.960
Where'd been.

01:25:13.960 --> 01:25:17.600
And I picked Panama City, Florida, which was close to home.

01:25:17.600 --> 01:25:19.400
And then your wife was able to be with you?

01:25:19.400 --> 01:25:20.400
And my wife came down there with me.

01:25:20.400 --> 01:25:21.400
I wanted to have two strikes.

01:25:21.400 --> 01:25:25.800
She came down, but the headquarters on base for Lil' Rican Airmen.

01:25:25.800 --> 01:25:30.160
And by that time, I had two kids born and girl.

01:25:30.160 --> 01:25:32.000
They were little kids.

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:35.960
And I went there with two strikes and I stayed there in May too, while I was there.

01:25:35.960 --> 01:25:39.240
And worked out well and I re-enlisted and started my Air Force career.

01:25:39.240 --> 01:25:45.440
So at re-enlistment time, I talked to my wife and said, look, now proud of talking with

01:25:45.440 --> 01:25:51.080
my wife, this worn off from Kentucky, White fellow.

01:25:51.080 --> 01:25:53.000
World War II was my boss.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:57.120
He was a communications officer over the whole thing.

01:25:57.120 --> 01:26:02.280
And I had left the comm center being a touch tape operator here and I was just clerk.

01:26:02.280 --> 01:26:05.880
I'm going to type on a tight rail then, okay?

01:26:05.880 --> 01:26:08.040
That's why I got my right working for him.

01:26:08.040 --> 01:26:10.440
He jacked me up, but I had to work though.

01:26:10.440 --> 01:26:14.440
Now I became a Western Union accountant clerk where I was doing all the tasks.

01:26:14.440 --> 01:26:19.440
And he said, he said, sorry, Damon, you come off a re-enlistment, but I talk about it.

01:26:19.440 --> 01:26:20.440
He said, what's your gun do?

01:26:20.440 --> 01:26:22.280
I said, well, I'm going back to Mississippi.

01:26:22.280 --> 01:26:25.200
To my dad, you know, he saw me on the issue.

01:26:25.200 --> 01:26:27.040
He said, you're crazy.

01:26:27.040 --> 01:26:28.760
He said, you only got 16 years to go.

01:26:28.760 --> 01:26:30.920
Well, you're already a status sergeant.

01:26:30.920 --> 01:26:34.120
So let me ask you, I don't know if I know enough about the military.

01:26:34.120 --> 01:26:37.680
So was your draft two years or four years?

01:26:37.680 --> 01:26:38.680
It was four years, two.

01:26:38.680 --> 01:26:39.680
It was a four year tour.

01:26:39.680 --> 01:26:40.680
Four years, four years tour.

01:26:40.680 --> 01:26:41.680
So, okay.

01:26:41.680 --> 01:26:45.440
So once you moved towards the air force, you had to have it longer tour.

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:46.440
Two more years.

01:26:46.440 --> 01:26:47.440
All right.

01:26:47.440 --> 01:26:49.960
So you had invested four years.

01:26:49.960 --> 01:26:53.560
I invested four years, but that gave me a chance to make enough right to where I can

01:26:53.560 --> 01:26:56.560
make a decision when I want to become a career in hindsight.

01:26:56.560 --> 01:27:00.400
And so that was enough for you to envision a career with the Air Force.

01:27:01.400 --> 01:27:05.800
And then when I told my boss, because his office is like that.

01:27:05.800 --> 01:27:09.360
And I'm in here, tight right, and I'm supposed to do this other work.

01:27:09.360 --> 01:27:11.600
He said, you're crazy.

01:27:11.600 --> 01:27:17.080
And he and the top sergeant in the outfit that who's in the office with him coming

01:27:17.080 --> 01:27:18.800
to say, you don't want to do that.

01:27:18.800 --> 01:27:23.320
Hey, I started explaining the Air Force benefits and then I got things going on, which I hadn't

01:27:23.320 --> 01:27:25.800
really zeroed in on.

01:27:25.800 --> 01:27:28.800
And so after I talked with my wife and told them about it, and I said, yeah, I'm real

01:27:28.800 --> 01:27:29.800
this.

01:27:29.800 --> 01:27:32.120
And I went back and I told them and said, yeah, Mr. He's one of them.

01:27:32.120 --> 01:27:34.320
And I said, Mr. Just, yes, I'm realist.

01:27:34.320 --> 01:27:35.320
He made a appointment.

01:27:35.320 --> 01:27:41.240
And I went on to talk to the commanding officer, squadron, leader, major.

01:27:41.240 --> 01:27:45.440
And he already received notification that I was going to reenlist.

01:27:45.440 --> 01:27:46.440
And I walked in.

01:27:46.440 --> 01:27:47.440
He shook me.

01:27:47.440 --> 01:27:49.280
He said, hey, Mr. Johnson, say you're going to reenlist.

01:27:49.280 --> 01:27:50.280
I said, yes, I'm going to do.

01:27:50.280 --> 01:27:51.280
He said, congratulations.

01:27:51.280 --> 01:27:54.760
Then they sent me off a reenlistment.

01:27:54.760 --> 01:27:55.760
Okay.

01:27:55.760 --> 01:28:01.240
And they were giving me a bonus for reenlisting.

01:28:01.240 --> 01:28:02.240
Yeah.

01:28:02.240 --> 01:28:05.680
And if you reenlist for four years, you get a certain amount.

01:28:05.680 --> 01:28:08.080
If you reenlist for six years, you get more money.

01:28:08.080 --> 01:28:10.880
Well, since I'm going, I went for six years.

01:28:10.880 --> 01:28:13.840
And when I went to the finance office, they paid us in cash.

01:28:13.840 --> 01:28:16.560
I had a stack of $20 bills that high.

01:28:16.560 --> 01:28:18.320
That's most money I've been sitting my life.

01:28:18.320 --> 01:28:21.360
And I said, oh, man, so you felt like you made a good decision.

01:28:21.360 --> 01:28:23.120
Oh, I went on to my wife, I was rich.

01:28:23.520 --> 01:28:26.040
So she lived there on beach, you know.

01:28:26.040 --> 01:28:28.160
And had bought me a little forward car.

01:28:28.160 --> 01:28:29.160
Yeah.

01:28:29.160 --> 01:28:30.160
And everything was going well.

01:28:30.160 --> 01:28:31.920
And that started my Air Force career.

01:28:31.920 --> 01:28:37.200
And the house was fire bombed in 1966.

01:28:37.200 --> 01:28:42.400
In 1964, my family and I had returned from Germany.

01:28:42.400 --> 01:28:46.920
And obviously, we'd been dead and my mom there in the family home.

01:28:46.920 --> 01:28:49.240
And my wife is from here also.

01:28:49.240 --> 01:28:51.880
So between the two families.

01:28:52.160 --> 01:28:58.640
I saw at that time that the racial tension was real high.

01:28:58.640 --> 01:29:03.240
And my dad was quite conscious there and there was safety.

01:29:03.240 --> 01:29:05.880
But being home and enjoying being home,

01:29:05.880 --> 01:29:08.200
I didn't really focus on it that much.

01:29:08.200 --> 01:29:12.520
Then I was assigned to March Air Base in California.

01:29:12.520 --> 01:29:16.360
And I moved my family there with me and got the kids involved in school.

01:29:16.360 --> 01:29:18.120
And at that time, I was,

01:29:22.040 --> 01:29:23.040
Master Sergeant.

01:29:25.160 --> 01:29:29.480
And I became,

01:29:30.440 --> 01:29:34.480
shifted in a big communications organization.

01:29:35.600 --> 01:29:38.360
And I didn't hear anything and moved from my dad.

01:29:39.360 --> 01:29:42.680
Because we didn't communicate that much because he had his thing going to head

01:29:42.680 --> 01:29:43.680
mind going.

01:29:43.680 --> 01:29:44.880
My Air Force career and kids in school now.

01:29:46.120 --> 01:29:50.320
And on the morning.

01:29:52.160 --> 01:29:58.240
Monday morning, January 10, 1966, I received a telephone call from one of my

01:29:58.240 --> 01:30:05.240
dad's sisters who lived in Compton, then South Central LA, Compton, California.

01:30:06.480 --> 01:30:08.480
And I was informed of what had happened.

01:30:08.480 --> 01:30:10.480
The house had been fire bombed.

01:30:10.480 --> 01:30:12.680
And it was like two or three o'clock in the morning,

01:30:12.680 --> 01:30:14.080
and built me up out of a deep sleep.

01:30:14.080 --> 01:30:19.120
I was living in my own house downtown, the boat house downtown, with my family.

01:30:20.120 --> 01:30:24.120
And that was really a shock.

01:30:25.640 --> 01:30:30.120
I wasn't too surprised because what I had seen, but at that time, it was a shock.

01:30:31.120 --> 01:30:34.120
So I worked my wife around and told her what had happened.

01:30:34.920 --> 01:30:40.720
And I proceeded then to get ready to go to work, put my uniform on.

01:30:41.320 --> 01:30:45.320
And so while sitting after I got ready to go, I had time to think.

01:30:46.320 --> 01:30:52.320
Couldn't call anybody because what the house had been burned destroyed.

01:30:53.320 --> 01:30:55.520
And there was no telephone communication.

01:30:55.520 --> 01:30:59.320
So I'm here and I just waiting on my, to find out what my next move is going to be.

01:30:59.320 --> 01:31:03.320
So in my thoughts, I said, you know what?

01:31:03.320 --> 01:31:09.320
I know the, how blacks are treated in the justice system.

01:31:09.320 --> 01:31:12.320
Because I'm a grown man, I'm 35 years old.

01:31:12.320 --> 01:31:14.320
In Mississippi.

01:31:14.320 --> 01:31:20.320
And something told me, go to the FBI office in Riverside.

01:31:21.320 --> 01:31:26.320
And tell them about what has happened and express my desire.

01:31:27.320 --> 01:31:30.320
What I would like to see happened in my dead's case.

01:31:30.320 --> 01:31:33.320
I reported downtown Riverside, California, Federal Building.

01:31:33.320 --> 01:31:37.320
I was standing outside the FBI office when they came to work.

01:31:37.320 --> 01:31:41.320
There's two or three gentlemen came in and regreated one another, went over to the office.

01:31:41.320 --> 01:31:43.320
It's going to help you and I told them about it.

01:31:43.320 --> 01:31:45.320
Let me see if we already know about it.

01:31:45.320 --> 01:31:49.320
Because they were keeping up with these five bombers apparently on the, on that system.

01:31:50.320 --> 01:31:57.320
And long story short, I says, I have one request.

01:31:57.320 --> 01:32:08.320
I do not want any law enforcement officers, people on my dead's case, known from Mississippi.

01:32:08.320 --> 01:32:09.320
I was outside of Mississippi.

01:32:09.320 --> 01:32:11.320
I'm all the way to the FBI.

01:32:11.320 --> 01:32:13.320
I have top secret DSI clearance.

01:32:13.320 --> 01:32:14.320
I'm all the way up.

01:32:14.320 --> 01:32:15.320
What's going on now?

01:32:15.320 --> 01:32:20.320
And that one, the FBI also looked at me and he says, hold on a minute.

01:32:20.320 --> 01:32:23.320
Are you telling me that you end up the integrity of the FBI?

01:32:23.320 --> 01:32:24.320
I never would forget.

01:32:24.320 --> 01:32:26.320
I'd like to record it on my brain.

01:32:26.320 --> 01:32:29.320
And I told him, I didn't see that.

01:32:29.320 --> 01:32:32.320
I told you what my desire was.

01:32:32.320 --> 01:32:37.320
And from that time on, I found out later that I was being trained.

01:32:37.320 --> 01:32:39.320
I was an observation.

01:32:39.320 --> 01:32:47.320
One of the reasons being is, on my security clearance and my position, because I was in charge of base-style communication

01:32:47.320 --> 01:32:53.320
percent of, at 50 people working and all kind of intelligence stuff, very super sensitive thing.

01:32:53.320 --> 01:33:01.320
And the commanding officer when I left going home, who was a colonel, called me in his office and told me, do not compromise my position.

01:33:01.320 --> 01:33:04.320
You know, how did they think you might do that?

01:33:04.320 --> 01:33:05.320
What was it?

01:33:05.320 --> 01:33:06.320
I had access to it.

01:33:06.320 --> 01:33:09.320
So they think, but what did they think you would do with it?

01:33:09.320 --> 01:33:16.320
Well, you know, we've had people, you know, disurden and going on and doing crazy stuff.

01:33:16.320 --> 01:33:20.320
Just want to let me know that my commitment was to the Air Force.

01:33:20.320 --> 01:33:22.320
Well, my commitment is also to my family.

01:33:22.320 --> 01:33:28.320
I'm not going to kill a career of 15 years going home, you know, and do some crazy stuff.

01:33:28.320 --> 01:33:30.320
No. But that was okay.

01:33:30.320 --> 01:33:36.320
And I don't recall him ever telling me, you know, he regret what happened to my dad, because I wasn't focused on that.

01:33:36.320 --> 01:33:42.320
But when I went by the first sergeant, you know, who was a good friend of mine, you know, big outfit and I know other people,

01:33:42.320 --> 01:33:45.320
he looked me as kind of shook his head like, dang.

01:33:45.320 --> 01:33:49.320
And the meantime, I went on in and started preparing to come home.

01:33:49.320 --> 01:33:58.320
And I arrived home. That was on, I left Los Angeles Airport midnight on that Monday night.

01:33:58.320 --> 01:34:06.320
I got reservations on, I arrived in New Orleans and next morning and got a plate coming out of New Orleans to home.

01:34:06.320 --> 01:34:10.320
And during my trip home, I saw this one guy on the plane.

01:34:10.320 --> 01:34:19.320
I didn't notice it at the time, but the same guy that I saw on the plane at boarder to plane at midnight in L.A.

01:34:19.320 --> 01:34:24.320
And we got New Orleans, had to change planes a couple of times because we were having difficulty.

01:34:24.320 --> 01:34:31.320
And finally, I called a bus and came on the bus when I got to the site. I saw the same guy again, but I never connected the dots.

01:34:31.320 --> 01:34:33.320
They already had somebody?

01:34:33.320 --> 01:34:35.320
I already had somebody on me.

01:34:35.320 --> 01:34:41.320
And that person stayed on me for a long time because when I got back to my job, I had to be at home for two weeks.

01:34:41.320 --> 01:34:46.320
And there, one of the guys in my department where all of the messages on the base, all kind of clear,

01:34:46.320 --> 01:34:55.320
I said, going through my facility that I'm in charge of, they never, never did identify me as being the guy who sees everything that go wrong.

01:34:55.320 --> 01:34:59.320
The message comes across to them about my activity.

01:34:59.320 --> 01:35:04.320
My analysis guy showed it to me.

01:35:04.320 --> 01:35:10.320
So then, you know, I said, hey, these people don't know I'm a Negro or whatever.

01:35:10.320 --> 01:35:13.320
And so I said, well, they've been keeping up with me.

01:35:13.320 --> 01:35:19.320
But in the meantime, coming home to bury my dad and what happened, this is the most essential part.

01:35:19.320 --> 01:35:35.320
My dad, the father of eight children, seven boys and a girl, seven of his sons, including me, served a total of 78 years on active duty,

01:35:35.320 --> 01:35:39.320
during the Korean and Vietnam era and beyond.

01:35:39.320 --> 01:35:49.320
We were serving our nation, protecting the very country that neglected to protect my family from the tourist forces here.

01:35:49.320 --> 01:35:55.320
My dad and mom slept in shifts for years, which my mom probably told you about.

01:35:55.320 --> 01:36:02.320
For years while we were throughout the world, what, protecting the nation and my country couldn't protect me.

01:36:02.320 --> 01:36:07.320
Coming home to that devastated site that morning when I arrived.

01:36:07.320 --> 01:36:12.320
And I looked at the burned off facilities, which you, I think, you've probably seen pictures of.

01:36:12.320 --> 01:36:16.320
And I went to the morgue and looked at my dad.

01:36:16.320 --> 01:36:23.320
That was probably the worst days of my life.

01:36:23.320 --> 01:36:25.320
I mean, that was horrible.

01:36:25.320 --> 01:36:30.320
But I, I said, hey, you're the oldest kid.

01:36:30.320 --> 01:36:33.320
You've got a responsibility.

01:36:33.320 --> 01:36:35.320
You've been around.

01:36:35.320 --> 01:36:39.320
Your mom, your sister, been burned.

01:36:39.320 --> 01:36:40.320
Your dad's dead.

01:36:40.320 --> 01:36:42.320
My family's homeless.

01:36:42.320 --> 01:36:44.320
The law enforcement people everywhere.

01:36:44.320 --> 01:36:46.320
The reporters everywhere.

01:36:46.320 --> 01:36:49.320
Kurosda and the Seekas everywhere to burn down site.

01:36:49.320 --> 01:36:51.320
Some grievings.

01:36:51.320 --> 01:36:53.320
Some, whatever.

01:36:53.320 --> 01:36:58.320
But I got to deal with this issue and then the burden is on my shoulder.

01:36:58.320 --> 01:36:59.320
Okay?

01:36:59.320 --> 01:37:08.320
And having that responsibility as I grew up in the Air Force, prepared me for a lot of tough stuff.

01:37:08.320 --> 01:37:11.320
But it was not prepared to deal with this.

01:37:11.320 --> 01:37:13.320
But I said, it's over now.

01:37:13.320 --> 01:37:14.320
You got to do it.

01:37:14.320 --> 01:37:16.320
So I just barked it out.

01:37:16.320 --> 01:37:18.320
And I started dealing with the objective.

01:37:18.320 --> 01:37:20.320
I mean, immediately.

01:37:20.320 --> 01:37:23.320
I was dead, you know, as far as I'm concerned.

01:37:23.320 --> 01:37:24.320
Yeah, he's dead.

01:37:24.320 --> 01:37:28.320
But I don't let this get in the way of what I have to do.

01:37:28.320 --> 01:37:31.320
Constantly, I got good family and I had some help.

01:37:31.320 --> 01:37:37.320
But the decision was on around me, being the oldest son, because that's just where we were raised.

01:37:37.320 --> 01:37:41.320
And in the meantime, that contact with my other brothers, my name was coming in.

01:37:41.320 --> 01:37:45.320
And the family didn't prepare for the funeral and all this other stuff.

01:37:45.320 --> 01:37:47.320
Now that was a very tough time.

01:37:47.320 --> 01:37:50.320
I don't know if there's never been another time in my life.

01:37:50.320 --> 01:37:55.320
And it wasn't my dad's death comes.

01:37:55.320 --> 01:38:02.320
But the way he died and the contribution he'd made society and the contributions he sent,

01:38:02.320 --> 01:38:07.320
all of us retired from the military and would auto-medist charge and would actulates.

01:38:07.320 --> 01:38:12.320
You know, five full of things that we did that we learned the home to do right.

01:38:12.320 --> 01:38:13.320
And we're good soldiers.

01:38:13.320 --> 01:38:16.320
There's no black mark nowhere and we deal with this.

01:38:16.320 --> 01:38:21.320
So, and I looked at it and I said, well, my praise for defending my country was to what?

01:38:21.320 --> 01:38:24.320
What happened to it?

01:38:24.320 --> 01:38:28.320
That's what my country thought on me, because this did not have to happen.

01:38:28.320 --> 01:38:34.320
The oath that my brothers not took, hey, we lived up to it.

01:38:34.320 --> 01:38:39.320
Wherever they were going to send us, that's where we were going to go and we were going to do what we had to do.

01:38:39.320 --> 01:38:46.320
That's the way we, but the oath that those people who took to protect my family, they did not do it.

01:38:46.320 --> 01:38:52.320
And I fought my country for not what, making them do that.

01:38:52.320 --> 01:38:57.320
Now, I still love my country, but I still don't say, hey, my country could have done a better than that.

01:38:57.320 --> 01:39:02.320
If I can do this for my country, if I can, my country could do this for my family.

01:39:02.320 --> 01:39:04.320
And it took me a while to get over that.

01:39:04.320 --> 01:39:08.320
But I never thought about being vindictive that ain't me.

01:39:08.320 --> 01:39:17.320
But you, these things go through because what you have to be denied the opportunity that you gave all you were for to try to have.

01:39:17.320 --> 01:39:20.320
And that was tough.

01:39:20.320 --> 01:39:26.320
When your father was killed, were all your brothers who served in the military?

01:39:26.320 --> 01:39:31.320
Were they already in the military or did some of them join after?

01:39:31.320 --> 01:39:34.320
No, no, no. All of us had gone in and drafted.

01:39:34.320 --> 01:39:36.320
Yes. Well, they said join.

01:39:36.320 --> 01:39:40.320
But they were in the military. I don't know how they, you know, why all of them got there.

01:39:40.320 --> 01:39:42.320
Being old as I was at first.

01:39:42.320 --> 01:39:45.320
When my dad was killed, it was for us on active duty.

01:39:45.320 --> 01:39:47.320
I was in California.

01:39:47.320 --> 01:39:51.320
My brother next to me, the second known, he was career.

01:39:51.320 --> 01:39:53.320
He was on Chemi Island off of Alaska.

01:39:53.320 --> 01:39:56.320
My other brother was in Germany and I had one in Florida.

01:39:56.320 --> 01:40:03.320
And my brother, Harold, who just returned from career and ended his commitment to the service.

01:40:03.320 --> 01:40:06.320
On a bloody discharge, he was in the house that night.

01:40:06.320 --> 01:40:11.320
So the time that my dad, my mom and dad were sleeping in shifts to avoid what eventually happened.

01:40:11.320 --> 01:40:15.320
They had five sons, served on active duty in the military.

01:40:15.320 --> 01:40:25.320
And for us four sons that come home in uniform and buried my dad because of what these race haters,

01:40:25.320 --> 01:40:28.320
all because he's the wrong race, he's the wrong color.

01:40:28.320 --> 01:40:30.320
But he's born in this country.

01:40:30.320 --> 01:40:34.320
He was a good citizen, well start of, a family good citizen.

01:40:34.320 --> 01:40:39.320
And as far as I'm concerned, we wouldn't better know about it, but hey, my family had,

01:40:39.320 --> 01:40:43.320
and as far as I'm going to do the good job and race, it must be good citizens.

01:40:43.320 --> 01:40:45.320
And we live by that code today.

01:40:45.320 --> 01:40:51.320
Did anybody at the time recognize that fact about all of you serving your country?

01:40:51.320 --> 01:40:55.320
Other than the fact that we came home, you know, we'd be in the newspaper,

01:40:55.320 --> 01:40:57.320
if this sergeant came home, that one came home.

01:40:57.320 --> 01:40:58.320
No, no.

01:40:58.320 --> 01:40:59.320
No special.

01:40:59.320 --> 01:41:00.320
No.

01:41:00.320 --> 01:41:01.320
No.

01:41:01.320 --> 01:41:02.320
And the contradiction you're pointing out?

01:41:02.320 --> 01:41:03.320
Right.

01:41:03.320 --> 01:41:05.320
Nobody pointed out.

01:41:05.320 --> 01:41:12.320
Can you talk about what your family's done over the years to try to pursue?

01:41:12.320 --> 01:41:18.320
You know, there's probably no justice in this case, but to make sure that some people were held accountable?

01:41:18.320 --> 01:41:20.320
Yes.

01:41:20.320 --> 01:41:26.320
My mom is a lady that I have the utmost respect for.

01:41:26.320 --> 01:41:29.320
And she gets that respect from all of us.

01:41:29.320 --> 01:41:33.320
You know, she's number one in our life.

01:41:33.320 --> 01:41:35.320
She's the leader of our family.

01:41:35.320 --> 01:41:40.320
Even though we were all men, she went through all this, and we never overshadow her.

01:41:40.320 --> 01:41:41.320
You may notice that.

01:41:41.320 --> 01:41:43.320
We don't do that.

01:41:43.320 --> 01:41:51.320
And as a result of what happened to our family, she chose not to leave.

01:41:51.320 --> 01:41:54.320
She chose to stay here because she had those two kids.

01:41:54.320 --> 01:41:55.320
She was a teacher.

01:41:55.320 --> 01:42:03.320
And she had brothers living in Washington another place that were financially in good shape.

01:42:03.320 --> 01:42:08.320
One brother, the dentist, others worked for the federal government in Washington at good jobs.

01:42:08.320 --> 01:42:11.320
They said, hey, leader please, come here.

01:42:11.320 --> 01:42:14.320
She thought she was on the ground.

01:42:14.320 --> 01:42:18.320
And she stayed, built a house on the same spot.

01:42:18.320 --> 01:42:23.320
And raised those two kids, Dennis and Betty, that she had by my dad,

01:42:23.320 --> 01:42:25.320
okay, my brother and my sister.

01:42:25.320 --> 01:42:27.320
We don't have no haves.

01:42:27.320 --> 01:42:32.320
Everybody's brothers and sisters sent in the college degrees.

01:42:32.320 --> 01:42:35.320
They were professionals and went all out in their life.

01:42:35.320 --> 01:42:38.320
And she built a home with assistance.

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:42.320
And continued her life, became an election commissioner.

01:42:42.320 --> 01:42:46.320
In the same district where my dad was killed for three terms.

01:42:46.320 --> 01:42:49.320
And she had more terms.

01:42:49.320 --> 01:42:54.320
And the whites put her in all because of the kind of life that she lived.

01:42:54.320 --> 01:42:56.320
It wasn't because they felt sorry for her.

01:42:56.320 --> 01:42:59.320
That was probably a part of it, a little sympathy there.

01:42:59.320 --> 01:43:05.320
But because of the life that she did and the way that she lived her life after this catastrophic event.

01:43:05.320 --> 01:43:10.320
And then she had to, what, live through all of these clansmen's trials.

01:43:10.320 --> 01:43:13.320
She testified over seven to something times.

01:43:13.320 --> 01:43:17.320
And after the 14 who did this were indicted.

01:43:17.320 --> 01:43:19.320
And they brought some to justice.

01:43:19.320 --> 01:43:24.320
And finally, they couldn't get soundbiles after they tried him four times.

01:43:24.320 --> 01:43:27.320
Because what the jury had clansmen in there.

01:43:27.320 --> 01:43:30.320
She went through a whole lot.

01:43:30.320 --> 01:43:35.320
And as a result, she maintained the family nucleus, the location.

01:43:35.320 --> 01:43:38.320
And we all came back home around her.

01:43:38.320 --> 01:43:42.320
And built for you see we are today.

01:43:42.320 --> 01:43:45.320
She held everything in tag.

01:43:45.320 --> 01:43:52.320
And to me, that demonstrate a whole lot about who we are as a family.

01:43:52.320 --> 01:43:54.320
And they know big eyes and little news.

01:43:54.320 --> 01:43:57.320
We just, we just a family committed to where we were raised.

01:43:57.320 --> 01:44:05.320
And we got a lady here that my dad chose to be his wife down the road that we totally respect to the end.

01:44:05.320 --> 01:44:09.320
And that we do.

01:44:09.320 --> 01:44:14.320
It's such a thing to have to go through.

01:44:14.320 --> 01:44:24.320
And it seems like that you all have handled it as well as anybody could.

01:44:24.320 --> 01:44:29.320
Coming out of this situation after we got the conviction of soundbowers.

01:44:29.320 --> 01:44:30.320
Did that help?

01:44:30.320 --> 01:44:34.320
Yeah, you know, soundbowers was, was, was in 1998.

01:44:34.320 --> 01:44:38.320
The Medgev was a case service, the opportunity for us to get soundbowers back in the courtroom.

01:44:38.320 --> 01:44:41.320
We won't go through all of that.

01:44:41.320 --> 01:44:46.320
Can you just, I mean, we know, but can you say who soundbowers is for people?

01:44:46.320 --> 01:44:47.320
Oh, yes, for sure.

01:44:47.320 --> 01:44:58.320
The soundbowers was the leader of the white nace of the Clucleic clan in Jones County in, in, in law of Mississippi area.

01:44:58.320 --> 01:45:12.320
And he had power that was equal to the governor's what while former clansmen told me that he was, he was highly regarded.

01:45:12.320 --> 01:45:15.320
And he could go to the governor's office anytime.

01:45:15.320 --> 01:45:24.320
And he had told former clansmen, other clansmen in his organization, you can kill a, kill a black male on Nigger and Mississippi.

01:45:24.320 --> 01:45:26.320
You don't have to worry about going jail.

01:45:26.320 --> 01:45:30.320
Now, I got this from former clansmen, okay?

01:45:30.320 --> 01:45:38.320
So sound, soundbowers was, was a man that was beyond reach during that error.

01:45:38.320 --> 01:45:50.320
And to get him back into the courtroom in 1998, which required a lot of work, a weed, our family worked with the, with the law enforcement people to get him back to the courtroom.

01:45:50.320 --> 01:45:55.320
And I was the primary leader on that with the assistance of the family.

01:45:55.320 --> 01:46:00.320
Now, but you got to have a spokesperson, my mom and I, and my brother Dennis, he helped a lot also.

01:46:00.320 --> 01:46:08.320
And we were, with the news media and all and created enough attention on it.

01:46:08.320 --> 01:46:16.320
Created, we created enough attention, you know, until we got to support of the community because what?

01:46:16.320 --> 01:46:28.320
We, we go through all these phases and only got five convictions out of the previous trials that it was held in the 1960s, late 1968, 6768.

01:46:28.320 --> 01:46:32.320
But we never could get Sam. Now we have a chance to get Sam.

01:46:32.320 --> 01:46:38.320
For Sam and Sam was convicted on the 21st of August,

01:46:38.320 --> 01:46:52.320
by jury verdict, 1998, somewhere around 22 and 3 o'clock a day I'll never forget, for what he had done.

01:46:52.320 --> 01:47:02.320
